ts must either be separated by a modal, such as “will”, “should” and “can”, or a finite auxiliary, which includes “be” or “do”. Often, this middle component is in its negated form, although one would occasionally come across split subjects without negation. This can be observed in ” There'd somebody who will answer the question in class.” %0a%3c %0a%3c Interestingly, there appears to be more than one type of split subject. Consider the following examples:%0a%3c 1.We hadn’t any of us done the assignment.%0a%3c 2.They don’t any of them want to miss the deadline.%0a%3c %0a%3c While this appears to follow the previous specifications for a split subject, there are minute differences that distinguish the two. In the above two examples, we observe that the indefinite components “any of us” and “any of them” specifies a distinct subset of a group, as opposed to “anybody”. Furthermore, the second component corresponds to the pronoun in the first component, as seen in “us” and “we. Empirically, speakers who find sentences containing the first type of split subject ungrammatical actually find accept sentences containing the second type of split subject. This suggests that there are two types of split subjects that originated from two different groups of Englishes.%0a%3c %0a%3c References:%0a%3c Zanuttini, Raffaella. 2013. Split subjects. Yale Grammatical Diversity Project: English in North America. (Available online at http://ygdp.yale.edu/phenomena/split-subjects. Accessed on 2021-04-10). Updated by Tom McCoy (2015) and Katie Martin (2018).%0a%3c %0a%3c [[#contentends]]%0a%3c ----%0a\ No newline at end of file%0a
